If there's nothing to eat, they won't come in and won't multiply if they occasionally do come in. Keep food in sealed containers like the refrigerator and jars, vacuum dust from carpets, corners and shelves, and vacuum or mop hard floors. Clean floors under items where dirt may settle, including sinks, refrigerators, and especially stoves.This is much easier and more effective than trying to keep up with chasing bugs one by one. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/b0/Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-3Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-3Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/b0/Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-3Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-3Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Don't pull on a gas stove or pull hard on a refrigerator with an ice maker to move it lest you damage the supply line. Try a vacuum cleaner extension, or temporarily removing the drawer under the stove, to get under them. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/ab/Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-3Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-3Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/ab/Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-3Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-3Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

For vacuuming things other than the floor, use a simple nozzle without electrical or moving parts which has been taken off the vacuum and cleaned. A brush nozzle generally won't scratch. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/3/38/Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-3Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-3Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/3/38/Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-3Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-3Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

A vacuum cleaner can be used to cut down the spider population immediately and vacuuming out the webs will stop the increase of spiders in future days and months. In removing a spiderweb, you remove the spider's home, the nursery for future baby spiders, and the spider's grocery store. (On occasion the spider web itself is actually consumed by the spider!) This is a pretty big deal since one of those egg sacks can have 300 little baby spiders in it. While most never make it to maturity, imagine roughly half becoming egg laying females. That's 150 times 300 eggs!Vacuum up every spiderweb you can find. By removing the web, you're removing all the comforts that the spider needs to survive and repopulate. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/5d/Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-4Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-4Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/5d/Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-4Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-4Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Use an extended vacuum end of a canister vacuum cleaner to reach high places. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/9/9f/Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-4Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-4Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/9/9f/Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-4Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-4Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

A hand-held vacuum is useful for the nooks and crannies where spiders tend to hide. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/6a/Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-4Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-4Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/6a/Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-4Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-4Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Moths flutter around, fall into your food and drink and can be costly to get rid of.Vacuum cracks between benches, counter tops, and under the refrigerator. Food particles from grains filter into all your cabinets from the counter tops; these particles find a resting place in the tightest cracks and float downward toward the fan under your refrigerator. These areas need a thorough vacuuming from time to time. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/bc/Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-5Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-5Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/bc/Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-5Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-5Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Vacuum the pantry shelves where the food is stored. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/9/9a/Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-5Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-5Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/9/9a/Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-5Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-5Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Look to the place where the ceiling and wall meet. Indian meal moths climb the wall and spin their silken cocoons at that point. At first glance they may look like spider webs, but webs or cocoons, get that vacuum out and suck them away! {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/aa/Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-5Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-5Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/aa/Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-5Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-5Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Dispose of the vacuum bag or contents outside in the trash can so that the pests are not reintroduced into the house. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/7a/Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-5Bullet4.jpg/v4-460px-Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-5Bullet4.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/7a/Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-5Bullet4.jpg/v4-760px-Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-5Bullet4.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

There are several types of cockroaches that may like your home. The first cockroach gets there through various means - flying through open windows, walking in the door but the most notorious the German cockroach has to be transported via your grocery bag, the cute little dresser from the garage sale or even in that sugar you borrowed from the neighbors. As a general rule, cockroaches lay about 30 eggs in what is called an ootheca or egg purse. Upon nearing maturity, these are dropped anywhere the roach might be.Due to airborne particulates from the cockroach fecal matter, the cockroach exoskeleton and various body parts left behind cockroaches can be a direct cause of respiratory ailments. A non-HEPA vacuum may exacerbate the problem, so only use a vacuum with a HEPA filter. A vacuum cleaner is particularly useful in the control of roaches because the ootheca is readily visible and quickly vacuumed up. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/0b/Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-7Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-7Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/0b/Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-7Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-7Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Look for the ootheca in drawers, on shelves, under cabinets or anywhere cockroaches my be living. Vacuum roaches, ootheca, and all. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/c/c4/Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-7Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-7Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/c/c4/Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-7Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-7Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

After vacuuming, wash the area with strong soap. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/a7/Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-7Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-7Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/a7/Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-7Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-7Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Dispose of the bag or contents direct into a trash can outside that is going to be collected shortly, so that you don't re-introduce the pests. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/11/Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-7Bullet4.jpg/v4-460px-Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-7Bullet4.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/11/Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-7Bullet4.jpg/v4-760px-Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-7Bullet4.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

If you've had an invasion of stink bugs in your home, the vacuum is a great way to collect them quickly without getting the stench all over you from accidental squashing. Simply vacuum them up from wherever they're resting (usually walls and windows), and dispose of appropriately.Stink bugs can also be vacuumed off exterior walls if your vacuum cleaner extends that far. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/3/3d/Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-8Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-8Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/3/3d/Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-8Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-8Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Other bugs you can remove this way include Western conifer seed bug and the box elder bug. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/59/Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-8Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-8Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/59/Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-8Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Do-Pest-Control-With-a-Vacuum-Cleaner-Step-8Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
